# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: china-national-beach-soccer-team
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] It was organised by Brazilian sports agency Koch Tavares (one of the founding partners of Beach Soccer Worldwide).
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] The tournament took place at Copacabana Beach in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] The hosts and heavy favourites Brazil won the tournament by beating the United States 8–1 in the final, coming from behind to claim their first world title.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] The tournament was immediately deemed a success, leading to the instant scheduling of a second World Cup the following year.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] In 1994, Koch Tavares organised the first international beach soccer competition in Brazil, the *Mundialito de beach soccer*, a small 4-team event, in view of understanding how commercially successful beach soccer could be in the region.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] It featured Brazil, Argentina, Italy and the United States and was dubbed an "unofficial World Cup".
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] The Mundialito was deemed a huge success, which gave Koch Tavares the incentive to organise a fully-fledged international competition.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] This conception materialised a year later in 1995 as this, the maiden Beach Soccer World Championships – a larger and longer eight team event compared to the Mundialito.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] The following format was decided upon by the organisers for the maiden edition of the championships: the eight participating nations competed in two groups of four teams in a round robin format.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] The top two teams progressed straight to the semi-finals from which point on the championship was played as a knock-out tournament until a winner was crowned with an additional match to determine third place.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] Furthermore, the Brazilian team was also revealed to the press and engaged in interviews.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] The presence of Zico as part of the Brazilian squad, who made over 70 appearances for the Brazilian national association football team, gained considerable attention in the local press prior to the start of the championship.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] Zico revealed at the launch he accepted an invitation from his friend and Brazilian team captain, Júnior, to play at the event, despite claiming to be "out of shape" now aged 41, having retired from football a year earlier.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] Following the launch, official training for the World Championships began the next day on January 19 on pitches external to the beach arena, in front of Copacabana Palace, concluding with training sessions inside the arena on January 23.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] The draw to split the eight teams into Groups A and B was conducted on January 21 at the Rio Internacional Hotel.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] Brazil and Argentina were allocated as heads of the two respective groups, with the other six teams then drawn to accompany them.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] The Championships were part of the 1st Olympic Summer Festival (*Festival Olímpico de Verão*), taking place in the Copacabana beach arena with a capacity of 12,000.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] Entry to all games was free of charge for fans.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] In total, US$1 million (1.6 million in 2017) was invested into the organisation of the tournament, including payment for the players who participated.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] There was no qualification process for the first Beach Soccer World Championships; nations were simply invited to play.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] However, such invites were *not* random – specific nations were summoned.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] To make up the numbers, the Netherlands and the United States, despite having never won a FIFA World Cup title, were also invited as "guests".
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/1995-beach-soccer-world-championships] Africa, Asia and Oceania were unrepresented.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The **2005 FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup** was the first edition of the FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup, an international beach soccer competition contest by men's national teams and organized by FIFA.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Overall, it was the 11th edition of a world cup in beach soccer since its establishment with the first *Beach Soccer World Championships* in 1995.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] It took place in at Copacabana Beach in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, between 8 and 15 May.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] France defeated Portugal 1–0 in a penalty shootout, following a 3–3 draw after extra-time, to win their first title.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The 12 teams present at the finals in Brazil were split into four groups of three teams.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Each team played the other two teams in its group in a round-robin format, with the top two teams advancing to the quarter-finals.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The quarter-finals, semi-finals and the final itself was played in the form of a knockout tournament.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] European teams gained qualification by finishing in the top three spots of the 2004 Euro Beach Soccer League.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The final spot was contested between the next four best teams in a small knockout tournament a few days before the World Cup began which saw Spain win.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] South American and North American qualification was gained by finishing in the top spots of the 2005 CONCACAF and CONMEBOL Beach Soccer Championship.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] This was the first edition of the World Cup in which every continent had a representative.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-afc-beach-soccer-championship] The **2006 AFC Beach Soccer championship** also known as the **2006 FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup qualifiers for (AFC)** was the first beach soccer championship for Asia, held in May 2006, in Dubai, United Arab Emirates.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-afc-beach-soccer-championship] Bahrain won the championship, with Japan finishing second and Iran winning the third place-play off, to claim third.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-afc-beach-soccer-championship] The three teams moved on to play in the 2006 FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil from 2 November – 12 November.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The **2006 FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup** was the second edition of the FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup, governed by FIFA.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Overall, this was the 12th edition of a world cup in beach soccer since the establishment of the *Beach Soccer World Championships* which ran from 1995–2004 but was not governed by FIFA.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] It took place in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, from 2–12 November 2006.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The winners of the tournament were hosts Brazil, who won their first FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup title and their tenth world title overall.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] After the 2005 World Cup, beach soccer continued to grow and spread worldwide at a fast rate.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Therefore, FIFA established the *FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup qualifiers*, to try to allow more nations to play in the World Cup, as well as getting more national teams involved in the sport.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] FIFA also increased the number of participating teams in the World Cup from 12 to a record-high 16 teams.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] This also meant that nations would no longer be invited to play in the World Cup but would have to qualify.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] African nations were allocated 2 berths at the World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The championship took place between September 28 and September 30, 2006.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Cameroon and Nigeria were the two finalists, meaning they both qualified for the World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Cameroon defeated Nigeria in the final to win the title.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Asian nations were allocated 3 berths at the World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The championship took place between May 22 and May 26, 2006.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Bahrain and Japan were the two finalists, meaning they both qualified for the World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Bahrain defeated Japan in the final to win the title.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Iran and China were knocked out in the semi-finals and played each other in the third place play off.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Iran beat China to claim the third berth at the World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] European nations were allocated 5 berths at the World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Instead of having a specific tournament for World Cup qualification, qualification was achieved through the *2006 Euro Beach Soccer League* which took place earlier in the year.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The nations who made it to the second stage of the Superfinal qualified to the World Cup being Spain, Portugal, Poland and Italy.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] To decide who would claim the fifth berth, the defeated nations in the competition came back to play in a straight knockout tournament, with the winner progressing to the World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The nation which won the tournament was France who beat Switzerland in the final.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] North, Central American and Caribbean nations were allocated 2 berths at the World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The championship took place between September 13 and September 17, 2006.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The United States and Canada were the two finalists, meaning they both qualified for the World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The United States defeated Canada in the final to win the title.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Oceanian nations were allocated 1 berth at the World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The championship took place between August 31 and September 3, 2006.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The Solomon Islands and Vanuatu were the two finalists.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The Solomon Islands defeated Vanuatu in the final to win the title and qualify for the World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] South American nations were allocated 3 berths at the World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The championship took place between March 5 and March 12, 2006.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Brazil and Uruguay were the two finalists, meaning they both qualified for the World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Brazil defeated Uruguay in the final to win the title.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Argentina and Venezuela were knocked out in the semi-finals and played each other in the third place play off.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Argentina beat Venezuela to claim the third berth at the World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] As with the previous FIFA editions of the World Cup held in Rio, the tournament once again took place at the Copacabana Beach Soccer Arena.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The 16 teams present at the finals in Brazil were split into 4 groups of 4 teams.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Each team played the other 3 teams in its group in a round-robin format, with the top two teams advancing to the quarter finals.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The quarter finals, semi finals and the final itself was played in the form of a knockout tournament.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2007-afc-beach-soccer-championship] The **2007 AFC Beach Soccer championship** also known as the **2007 FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup qualifiers for (AFC)** was the second beach soccer championship for Asia, held in August 2007, in Dubai, United Arab Emirates.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2007-afc-beach-soccer-championship] The United Arab Emirates won the championship, with Japan finishing second and Iran winning the third place-play off, to claim third.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2007-afc-beach-soccer-championship] The three teams moved on to play in the 2007 FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil from 2 November – 11 November.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2008-afc-beach-soccer-championship] The **2008 AFC Beach Soccer Championship**, also known as the **2008 FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup qualifiers for (AFC)**, was the third beach soccer championship for Asia, held in May 2008, in Dubai, United Arab Emirates.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2008-afc-beach-soccer-championship] The three teams moved on to play in the 2008 FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup in Marseille, France, from 17 July – 28 July.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2009-afc-beach-soccer-championship] The **2009 AFC Beach Soccer Championship** was a qualifying tournament held during **7–11 November 2009** in Dubai, United Arab Emirates that determined which two participants will represent the AFC region at the 2009 FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2009-afc-beach-soccer-championship] The seven nation tournament consisted of two groups.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2009-afc-beach-soccer-championship] The teams played each other once in their group during the group stage.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2009-afc-beach-soccer-championship] The top two teams in each group advanced to the semifinals.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/2009-afc-beach-soccer-championship] The semifinal winners qualified for the 2009 FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/china-national-beach-soccer-team] The **China national beach soccer team** represents People's Republic of China in international beach soccer competitions.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/china-national-beach-soccer-team] They have never qualified for the FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/china-national-beach-soccer-team] Note: Flags indicate national team as defined under FIFA eligibility rules; some limited exceptions apply.
[src:china-national-beach-soccer-team/china-national-beach-soccer-team] Players may hold more than one non-FIFA nationality.
